data.content:
This is the **C# 14 span overload resolution** breaking change. Here's what's happening:

### The Problem

In C# 14, new built-in conversions from arrays to `Span<T>`/`ReadOnlySpan<T>` cause the compiler to resolve `array.Contains(num)` to **`MemoryExtensions.Contains`** (span-based) instead of **`Enumerable.Contains`**. Expression trees cannot represent span-based method calls, so this **throws at runtime** when the compiled expression is invoked.

### The Fix

Force the call to bind to `Enumerable.Contains` by casting the array to `IEnumerable<T>`:

```csharp
// Option 1: Use .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: Explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);

// Option 3: Cast to IEnumerable<int>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);
```

Any of these disambiguate overload resolution so the LINQ `Enumerable.Contains` method is selected instead of the span-based `MemoryExtensions.Contains`.
